                <section class="exc-content">
            <div class="container">
                <div class="exc-container">
                                                                                                        <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">How To Do</h2>
                                    <ol><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Start by standing with your feet shoulder-width apart to aid your balance.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Hold a dumbbell with both hands. Your palms should face the underside of the top-weight plate, and your thumbs should be wrapped around the handle.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Lift the dumbbell over your head until your arms are fully extended. The outside edge of the top weight should be pointing up. </span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Keep your elbows close to your head with your upper arms perpendicular to the floor.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Begin lowering the dumbbell slowly behind your head by bending the elbows. Keep your upper arms stationary and tucked close to your ears.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">As you lower the weight, exhale out of your nose.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Continue lowering until your forearms touch your biceps or you feel a good stretch in your triceps.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">As you breathe in, press the dumbbell back up to the starting position by extending your elbows. Focus on using only your triceps to lift the weight.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Do not lock your elbows at the top of the movement to maintain tension on the triceps.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Repeat as necessary.</span></li></ol>                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">Tips From Expert</h2>
                                    <ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Ensure that your wrists remain straight throughout the entire tricep extension. To help you remember, at the top of the lift, keep the front of the dumbbell parallel to the wall. At the bottom, aim to have the bottom of the dumbbell parallel to the floor.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">At the bottom of the movement, resist the urge to allow your elbows to flair out to the side. This will help lengthen the entire triceps muscles, ensuring better activation.</span></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Try not to use momentum to lift the weight. Instead, focus on using slow and controlled movement during the lowering and lifting phases.</span></li></ul>                                                                    </div>
                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">Optimal Sets and Reps</h2>
                                    <p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Now that you know how to perform the standing overhead tricep extension, it’s time to incorporate it into your workout. Below, you’ll find </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7927075/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">evidence-based loading recommendations</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> for each training style.</span></p>                                                                                <div style="overflow: auto">
                                                <figure class="wp-block-table">
                                                    <table>
                                                        <thead>
                                                            <tr>
                                                                <th>Training Type</th>
                                                                <th>Sets</th>
                                                                                                                                    <th>Reps</th>
                                                                                                                            </tr>
                                                        </thead>
                                                        <tbody>
                                                                                                                            <tr>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                        <td>Strength Training</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                <td>3–4</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                <td>4–6</td>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        </tr>
